IBM HYBRID CLOUD ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW
-----------------------------------------
IBM defines hybrid cloud as an environment combining on-premises, private cloud,
public cloud, and edge settings into a single, flexible managed IT infrastructure.

IBM's position: Hybrid cloud is not just a deployment option — it is the default
architecture for enterprise digital transformation. Enterprises rarely move entirely
to public cloud; they need to connect legacy on-premises systems with cloud-native applications.

IBM's hybrid cloud platform is built on:
- IBM Cloud (public cloud infrastructure)
- Red Hat OpenShift (container orchestration — runs consistently on any cloud or on-premises)
- IBM Watson / watsonx (AI and data platform)
- IBM Security services (compliance, secrets management, key management)

IBM WELL-ARCHITECTED FRAMEWORK
--------------------------------
IBM's Well-Architected Framework provides best practices for designing secure,
performant hybrid cloud solutions. It has five pillars:

PILLAR 1: SECURITY
- Zero-trust security model — never trust, always verify
- Identity and Access Management (IAM) with least-privilege principles
- Secrets Manager for API keys, passwords, certificates (never hardcode secrets)
- Key Protect for encryption key management
- Security and Compliance Center for continuous compliance monitoring
- All data encrypted in transit (TLS 1.2+) and at rest

PILLAR 2: RELIABILITY
- Multi-zone deployment — spread across at least 2 availability zones
- Health checks and automated recovery from failures
- Circuit breaker patterns to prevent cascade failures
- Defined Recovery Time Objective (RTO) and Recovery Point Objective (RPO)
- Regular disaster recovery testing — "game day" exercises

PILLAR 3: PERFORMANCE
- Horizontal scaling — add instances, not bigger instances
- CDN for static assets
- Caching layers (Redis, Memcached) before database calls
- Database query optimization and indexing
- Performance SLOs defined before deployment, not after complaints

PILLAR 4: COST OPTIMIZATION
- Right-sizing — don't over-provision infrastructure
- Auto-scaling to match demand
- Reserved capacity for predictable base load, on-demand for peaks
- Tagging strategy for cost attribution by project, squad, environment
- Regular architecture reviews to decommission unused resources

PILLAR 5: OPERATIONAL EXCELLENCE
- Infrastructure as Code (IaC) — Terraform for all infrastructure
- Everything in source control — infrastructure, configuration, pipelines
- Automated runbooks for common operational tasks
- Observability built in from day one (not retrofitted)
- Blameless postmortem culture after incidents

MICROSERVICES ARCHITECTURE @ IBM
----------------------------------
IBM's position: Microservices are the default architecture for new cloud-native
applications. Monoliths are appropriate for simple applications early in their lifecycle,
but modern enterprise applications should be built as microservices.

IBM definition: A microservices architecture is one in which an application is
composed of many discrete, network-connected components (microservices), each
responsible for a single business capability.

IBM MICROSERVICES PRINCIPLES:
- Single responsibility — each microservice does one thing well
- Independent deployability — each service has its own CI/CD pipeline to production
- Loose coupling — services communicate via APIs or events, not direct database calls
- High cohesion — related functionality lives together in the same service
- Resilience — failure of one service does not cascade to others
- Observability — each service emits logs, metrics, and traces

MICROSERVICES COMMUNICATION PATTERNS:
1. Synchronous REST API — service calls another service's HTTP endpoint
   Use when: immediate response needed, request-response pattern
   IBM tooling: IBM API Connect (API gateway and management)

2. Asynchronous messaging — service publishes event, others subscribe
   Use when: decoupled processing, eventual consistency acceptable
   IBM tooling: IBM Event Streams (Apache Kafka managed service)

3. Service mesh — handles service-to-service communication with security and observability
   IBM tooling: Red Hat OpenShift Service Mesh (Istio-based)

IBM MIGRATION STRATEGIES (THE 6 Rs)
--------------------------------------
IBM uses the "6 Rs" framework for cloud migration decisions:

RETAIN: Keep on-premises — too risky, too costly, or not worth migrating yet
RETIRE: Decommission — application no longer needed
REHOST ("Lift and Shift"): Move VM to cloud with no changes
  Pros: Fast, low risk. Cons: No cloud-native benefits. Cost may not improve.
  IBM tooling: IBM Cloud for VMware, bare metal servers

REPLATFORM ("Lift and Optimize"): Move with minor modifications
  Example: Move Java app from WebSphere on-premises to WebSphere Liberty on IBM Cloud
  IBM tooling: IBM WebSphere Transformation Advisor

REFACTOR / RE-ARCHITECT: Break monolith into microservices
  Most valuable, most expensive. Only do this if scale/agility requirements demand it.
  IBM pattern: Strangler Fig — incrementally carve microservices from the monolith,
  routing traffic away from the old system over time.
  IBM tooling: Red Hat OpenShift, IBM Mono2Micro (AI-assisted decomposition)

REPLACE: Swap for SaaS alternative
  Example: Replace custom HR system with Workday SaaS
  IBM role: Integration and migration services

