- IBM DevOps Insights — aggregate test and deployment data across toolchains

IBM DEVSECOPS REFERENCE ARCHITECTURE
----------------------------------------
IBM's DevSecOps deployable architecture is a pre-built, deployable solution for
setting up a secure CI/CD pipeline on IBM Cloud.

It automatically provisions:
- Git repository (IBM-hosted GitLab or GitHub integration)
- Tekton-based CI pipeline (runs on every pull request)
- Tekton-based CD pipeline (runs on merge to main, deploys to target environment)
- Container Registry with vulnerability scanning on every image build
- Secrets Manager integration (no secrets in code or pipeline config)
- Key Protect for encryption
- IBM Security and Compliance Center for compliance checks
- IBM DevOps Insights for test result aggregation and deployment risk analysis

Pipeline stages (IBM standard):
1. Source — code commit triggers pipeline
2. Code scan — Code Risk Analyzer runs SAST analysis
3. Unit tests — all unit tests must pass (100% pass rate required)
4. Container build — Docker image built
5. Container scan — Vulnerability Advisor scans image
6. Integration tests — integration test suite runs against dev environment
7. Compliance check — Security and Compliance Center validates policy
8. Deploy to staging — automated deployment
9. Acceptance tests — end-to-end test suite
10. Approval gate — human approval required before production
11. Deploy to production — canary or blue-green deployment
12. Post-deployment monitoring — health checks, alerts configured

IBM HYBRID CLOUD INTEGRATION PATTERNS
----------------------------------------
Enterprise applications require integration between cloud-native services and
on-premises legacy systems. IBM identifies three macro integration patterns:

INTRA-CLOUD INTEGRATION:
Services within the same cloud platform communicate via internal APIs or event streams.
Pattern: Microservice A calls Microservice B's REST API via service mesh.
IBM tooling: OpenShift Service Mesh, IBM Event Streams (Kafka), IBM API Connect

INTER-CLOUD INTEGRATION:
Services across different cloud platforms (IBM Cloud + AWS + Azure + GCP).
Pattern: Event-driven integration via Kafka; API gateway for synchronous calls.
Challenge: Latency, security, data residency compliance.
IBM tooling: IBM Event Streams, IBM API Connect, IBM MQ

CLOUD TO ON-PREMISES INTEGRATION:
Cloud-native applications integrating with on-premises Systems of Record (SoR).
Pattern: API layer in front of legacy system (adapter pattern).
IBM tooling: IBM App Connect Enterprise, IBM MQ, IBM DataStage
IBM recommendation: Never expose on-premises database directly to cloud services.
Always put an API or integration service layer in between.

IBM RED HAT OPENSHIFT — WHY IBM USES IT
-----------------------------------------
Red Hat OpenShift is IBM's preferred container orchestration platform.
IBM acquired Red Hat in 2019 for $34 billion — their largest acquisition.

Why OpenShift over plain Kubernetes:
- Runs on ANY cloud (IBM Cloud, AWS, Azure, GCP) AND on-premises — true hybrid portability
- Pre-integrated security (Pod Security Admission, Security Context Constraints)
- Built-in CI/CD tooling (OpenShift Pipelines = Tekton, OpenShift GitOps = ArgoCD)
- Developer experience (OpenShift Web Console, developer topology view)
- Enterprise support — IBM/Red Hat SLA, not community support
- Consistent operational model across environments — same commands, same tooling

IBM's pitch to clients: "Build once on OpenShift, run anywhere."
An application containerized on OpenShift can be migrated from AWS to IBM Cloud
to on-premises without code changes — only configuration changes.

IBM AI ARCHITECTURE — WATSONX
--------------------------------
IBM watsonx is IBM's enterprise AI platform. Three components:

WATSONX.AI:
- Foundation model studio — access to IBM Granite models and open-source models
- Prompt engineering and fine-tuning UI
- Model evaluation and benchmarking
- Model deployment to production APIs
- Key use cases: text generation, summarization, classification, code generation, RAG

WATSONX.DATA:
- Open lakehouse architecture combining data warehouse and data lake
- Uses Apache Iceberg open table format — avoids vendor lock-in
- Query data across IBM Cloud, AWS, Azure, on-premises from single interface
- Connect to existing data sources without moving data
- IBM Manta for data lineage — understand where data came from

WATSONX.GOVERNANCE:
- AI risk and compliance management
- Monitor AI models for bias, drift, and factual accuracy
- Automated compliance reports for AI regulations (EU AI Act, etc.)
- Fact sheets for each AI model — automated documentation

